# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: snomed-terminology
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:snomed-terminology/medical-classification] A **medical classification** is used to transform descriptions of medical diagnoses or procedures into standardized statistical code in a process known as clinical coding.
[src:snomed-terminology/medical-classification] Diagnosis classifications list diagnosis codes, which are used to track diseases and other health conditions, inclusive of chronic diseases such as diabetes mellitus and heart disease, and infectious diseases such as norovirus, the flu, and athlete's foot.
[src:snomed-terminology/medical-classification] Procedure classifications list procedure codes, which are used to capture interventional data.
[src:snomed-terminology/medical-classification] There are country specific standards and international classification systems.
[src:snomed-terminology/medical-classification] Many different medical classifications exist, though they occur in two main groupings: *Statistical classifications* and *Nomenclatures*.
[src:snomed-terminology/medical-classification] A statistical classification brings together similar clinical concepts and groups them into categories.
[src:snomed-terminology/medical-classification] The number of categories is limited so that the classification does not become too big.
[src:snomed-terminology/medical-classification] An example of this is used by the International Statistical Classification of Diseases and Related Health Problems (known as ICD).
[src:snomed-terminology/medical-classification] ICD-10 groups diseases of the circulatory system into one "chapter", known as Chapter IX, covering codes I00–I99.
[src:snomed-terminology/medical-classification] One of the codes in this chapter (I47.1) has the code title (rubric) *Supraventricular tachycardia*.
[src:snomed-terminology/medical-classification] However, there are several other clinical concepts that are also classified here.
[src:snomed-terminology/medical-classification] Among them are paroxysmal atrial tachycardia, paroxysmal junctional tachycardia, auricular tachycardia and nodal tachycardia.
[src:snomed-terminology/medical-classification] Another feature of statistical classifications is the provision of residual categories for "other" and "unspecified" conditions that do not have a specific category in the particular classification.
[src:snomed-terminology/medical-classification] In a nomenclature there is a separate listing and code for every clinical concept.
[src:snomed-terminology/medical-classification] So, in the previous example, each of the listed tachycardias would have its own code.
[src:snomed-terminology/medical-classification] This makes nomenclatures unwieldy for compiling health statistics.
[src:snomed-terminology/medical-classification] The World Health Organization (WHO) maintains several internationally endorsed classifications designed to facilitate the comparison of health related data within and across populations and over time as well as the compilation of nationally consistent data.
[src:snomed-terminology/medical-classification] Some of these international standards have been revised and adapted by various countries for national use.
[src:snomed-terminology/medical-classification] Derived classifications are based on the WHO reference classifications (i.e., ICD and ICF).
[src:snomed-terminology/medical-classification] Several countries have developed their own version of WHO-FIC publications, which go beyond a local language translation.
[src:snomed-terminology/medical-classification] Related classifications in the WHO-FIC are those that partially refer to the reference classifications, e.g., only at specific levels.
[src:snomed-terminology/medical-classification] ICD versions before ICD-9 are not in use anywhere.
[src:snomed-terminology/medical-classification] ICD-9 was published in 1977, and superseded by ICD-10 in 1994.
[src:snomed-terminology/medical-classification] The last version of ICD-10 was published in 2019, and it was replaced by ICD-11 on 1 January 2022.
[src:snomed-terminology/medical-classification] As of February 2022, 35 of the 194 member states have made the transition to the latest version of the ICD.
[src:snomed-terminology/medical-classification] The International Classification of Procedures in Medicine (ICPM) is a procedural classification that has not updated since 1989, and will be replaced by ICHI.
[src:snomed-terminology/medical-classification] National adaptions of the ICPM includes OPS-301, which is the official German procedural classification.
[src:snomed-terminology/medical-classification] International Classification of External Causes of Injury (ICECI) was last updated in 2003 and, with the development ICD-11, is no longer maintained.
[src:snomed-terminology/medical-classification] The concepts of ICECI are represented within ICD-11 as extension codes.
[src:snomed-terminology/medical-classification] The categories in a diagnosis classification classify diseases, disorders, symptoms and medical signs.
[src:snomed-terminology/medical-classification] The categories in a procedure classification classify specific health interventions undertaken by health professionals.
[src:snomed-terminology/medical-classification] Drugs are often grouped into drug classes.
[src:snomed-terminology/medical-classification] National Drug File-Reference Terminology was a terminology maintained by the Veterans Health Administration (VHA).
[src:snomed-terminology/medical-classification] Medication Reference Terminology (MED-RT) is a terminology created and maintained by Veterans Health Administration in the United States.
[src:snomed-terminology/medical-classification] In 2018, it replaced NDF-RT that was used during 2005–2017.
[src:snomed-terminology/medical-classification] Med-RT is not included in RxNorm but is included in National Library of Medicine's UMLS Metathesaurus.
[src:snomed-terminology/medical-classification] Prior 2017, NDF-RT was included in RxNorm.
[src:snomed-terminology/medical-classification] The first release of MED-RT was in the spring of 2018.
[src:snomed-terminology/medical-classification] The Systematized Nomenclature of Medicine (SNOMED) is the most widely recognised nomenclature in healthcare.
[src:snomed-terminology/medical-classification] Its current version, SNOMED Clinical Terms (SNOMED CT), is intended to provide a set of concepts and relationships that offers a common reference point for comparison and aggregation of data about the health care process.
[src:snomed-terminology/medical-classification] SNOMED CT is often described as a reference terminology.
[src:snomed-terminology/medical-classification] SNOMED CT contains more than 311,000 active concepts with unique meanings and formal logic-based definitions organised into hierarchies.
[src:snomed-terminology/medical-classification] SNOMED CT can be used by anyone with an Affiliate License, 40 low income countries defined by the World Bank or qualifying research, humanitarian and charitable projects.
[src:snomed-terminology/medical-classification] SNOMED CT is designed to be managed by computer, and it is a complex relationship concepts.
[src:snomed-terminology/medical-classification] The International Classification of Disease (ICD) is the most widely recognized medical classification.
[src:snomed-terminology/medical-classification] Maintained by the World Health Organization (WHO), its primary purpose is to categorise diseases for morbidity and mortality reporting.
[src:snomed-terminology/medical-classification] However the coded data is often used for other purposes too; including reimbursement practices such as medical billing.
[src:snomed-terminology/medical-classification] ICD has a hierarchical structure, and coding in this context, is the term applied when representations are assigned to the words they represent.
[src:snomed-terminology/medical-classification] Coding diagnoses and procedures is the assignment of codes from a code set that follows the rules of the underlying classification or other coding guidelines.
[src:snomed-terminology/medical-classification] The current version of the ICD, ICD-10, was endorsed by WHO in 1990.
[src:snomed-terminology/medical-classification] WHO Member states began using the ICD-10 classification system from 1994 for both morbidity and mortality reporting.
[src:snomed-terminology/medical-classification] The exception was the US, who only began using it for reporting mortality in 1999 whilst continuing to use ICD-9-CM for morbidity reporting.
[src:snomed-terminology/medical-classification] The US only adopted its version of ICD-10 in October 2015.
[src:snomed-terminology/medical-classification] The delay meant it was unable to compare US morbidity data with the rest of the world during this period.
[src:snomed-terminology/medical-classification] The next major version of the ICD, ICD-11, was ratified by the 72nd World Health Assembly on 25 May 2019, and member countries have been able to report data using ICD-11 codes since 1 January 2022.
[src:snomed-terminology/medical-classification] ICD-11 is a fully digital product with integration of clinical terminology and classification.
[src:snomed-terminology/medical-classification] It allows documentation at any level of detail.
[src:snomed-terminology/medical-classification] It includes extension codes, a terminology system, with medicaments, chemicals, infections agents, histopathology, anatomy and mechanisms, objects and animals, and other elements that serve to describe sources of injury or harm.
[src:snomed-terminology/medical-classification] SNOMED CT and ICD were originally designed for different purposes and each should be used for the purposes for which they were designed.
[src:snomed-terminology/medical-classification] As a core terminology for the EHR, SNOMED CT and ICD-11 provide a common language that enables a consistent way of capturing, and sharing health data across specialities and sites of care.
[src:snomed-terminology/medical-classification] SNOMED is a highly detailed terminology designed for input not reporting, without a specific use case.
[src:snomed-terminology/medical-classification] ICD-11 and SNOMED, are clinically based, and document whatever is needed for patient care.
[src:snomed-terminology/medical-classification] In contrast to SNOMED, ICD-11 allows full clinical documentation while permitting internationally agreed statistical aggregation for specific use cases.
[src:snomed-terminology/medical-classification] SNOMED CT and ICD are used directly by healthcare providers during the process of care, in addition, ICD can be also used for coding after the episode of care, in lower technology environments.
[src:snomed-terminology/medical-classification] SNOMED CT has multiple hierarchy, whereas there is single primary hierarchy for ICD-11 with alternative multiple hierarchies.
[src:snomed-terminology/medical-classification] SNOMED CT concepts are defined logically by their attributes, as is the case in ICD-11, that in addition has textual rules and definitions.
[src:snomed-terminology/medical-classification] The National Library of Medicine (NLM) maps ICD-9-CM, ICD-10-CM, ICD-10-PCS, and other classification systems to SNOMED.
[src:snomed-terminology/medical-classification] Data Mapping is the process of identifying relationships between two distinct data models.
[src:snomed-terminology/medical-classification] Veterinary medical codes include the VeNom Coding Group, the U.S.
[src:snomed-terminology/medical-classification] Animal Hospital Codes, and the Veterinary Extension to SNOMED CT (VetSCT).
[src:snomed-terminology/snomed-ct] SNOMED CT is maintained and distributed by SNOMED International, an international non-profit standards development organization, located in London, UK.
[src:snomed-terminology/snomed-ct] SNOMED International is the trading name of the International Health Terminology Standards Development Organisation (IHTSDO), established in 2007.
[src:snomed-terminology/snomed-ct] SNOMED CT provides for consistent information interchange and is fundamental to an interoperable electronic health record.
[src:snomed-terminology/snomed-ct] It provides a consistent means to index, store, retrieve, and aggregate clinical data across specialties and sites of care.
[src:snomed-terminology/snomed-ct] It also helps in organizing the content of electronic health records systems by reducing the variability in the way data are captured, encoded and used for clinical care of patients and research.
[src:snomed-terminology/snomed-ct] SNOMED CT can be used to directly record clinical details of individuals in electronic patient records.
[src:snomed-terminology/snomed-ct] It also provides the user with a number of linkages to clinical care pathways, shared care plans and other knowledge resources, in order to facilitate informed decision-making, and to support long-term patient care.
[src:snomed-terminology/snomed-ct] The availability of free automatic coding tools and services, which can return a ranked list of SNOMED CT descriptors to encode any clinical report, could help healthcare professionals to navigate the terminology.
[src:snomed-terminology/snomed-ct] SNOMED CT is a terminology that can cross-map to other international standards and classifications.
[src:snomed-terminology/snomed-ct] Specific language editions are available which augment the international edition and can contain language translations, as well as additional national terms.
[src:snomed-terminology/snomed-ct] For example, SNOMED CT-AU, released in December 2009 in Australia, is based on the international version of SNOMED CT, but encompasses words and ideas that are clinically and technically unique to Australia.
[src:snomed-terminology/snomed-ct] SNOMED started in 1965 as a Systematized Nomenclature of Pathology (SNOP) and was further developed into a logic-based health care terminology.
[src:snomed-terminology/snomed-ct] The final product was released in January 2002.
[src:snomed-terminology/snomed-ct] The International Health Terminology Standards Development Organisation now considers SNOMED CT to be a brand name rather than an acronym.
[src:snomed-terminology/snomed-ct] Previously SNOMED was an acronym of Systematized Nomenclature Of Medicine, but it lost that meaning when SNOMED was combined with CTV3 (Clinical Terms Version 3) into the merged product called SNOMED Clinical Terms, which was shortened to SNOMED CT.
[src:snomed-terminology/snomed-ct] The historical strength of SNOMED was its coverage of medical specialties.
[src:snomed-terminology/snomed-ct] SNOMED RT, with over 120,000 concepts, was designed to serve as a common reference terminology for the aggregation and retrieval of pathology health care data recorded by multiple organizations and individuals.
[src:snomed-terminology/snomed-ct] The strength of CTV3 was its terminologies for general practice.
[src:snomed-terminology/snomed-ct] CTV3, with 200,000 interrelated concepts, was used for storing structured information about primary care encounters in individual, patient-based records.
[src:snomed-terminology/snomed-ct] The January 2020 release of the SNOMED CT International Edition included more than 350,000 concepts.
[src:snomed-terminology/snomed-ct] The NLM negotiation team was led by Betsy Humphreys, and the contract provided NLM with a perpetual license for the core SNOMED CT (in Spanish and English) and its ongoing updates.
[src:snomed-terminology/snomed-ct] In April 2007, SNOMED CT intellectual property rights were transferred from the CAP to the International Health Terminology Standards Development Organisation (IHTSDO) in order to promote international adoption and use of SNOMED CT.
[src:snomed-terminology/snomed-ct] SNOMED CT is a multinational and multilingual terminology, which can manage different languages and dialects.
[src:snomed-terminology/snomed-ct] SNOMED CT is currently available in American English, British English, Spanish, Danish and Swedish, with other translations underway or nearly completed in French and Dutch.
[src:snomed-terminology/snomed-ct] SNOMED CT cross maps to other terminologies, such as: ICD-9-CM, ICD-10, ICD-O-3, ICD-10-AM, Laboratory LOINC and OPCS-4.
[src:snomed-terminology/snomed-ct] It supports ANSI, DICOM, HL7, and ISO standards.
[src:snomed-terminology/snomed-ct] **Reference Sets** – used to group Concepts or Descriptions into sets, including reference sets and cross-maps to other classifications and standards.
[src:snomed-terminology/snomed-ct] SNOMED CT "Concepts" are representational units that categorize all the things that characterize healthcare processes and need to be recorded therein.
[src:snomed-terminology/snomed-ct] In 2011, SNOMED CT included more than 311,000 concepts, which are uniquely identified by a concept ID, e.g. the concept 22298006 refers to *Myocardial infarction*.
[src:snomed-terminology/snomed-ct] All SNOMED CT concepts are organized into acyclic taxonomic (is-a) hierarchies; for example, *Viral pneumonia* IS-A *Infectious pneumonia* IS-A *Pneumonia* IS-A *Lung disease*.
[src:snomed-terminology/snomed-ct] Concepts may have multiple parents, for example *Infectious pneumonia* is also a child of *Infectious disease*.
[src:snomed-terminology/snomed-ct] The taxonomic structure allows data to be recorded and later accessed at different levels of aggregation.
[src:snomed-terminology/snomed-ct] SNOMED CT concepts are linked by approximately 1,360,000 links, called *relationships*.
[src:snomed-terminology/snomed-ct] Concepts are further described by various clinical terms or phrases, called Descriptions, which are divided into *Fully Specified Names* (FSNs), *Preferred Terms* (PTs), and *Synonyms*.
[src:snomed-terminology/snomed-ct] Each Concept has exactly one FSN, which is unique across all of SNOMED CT.
[src:snomed-terminology/snomed-ct] It has, in addition, exactly one PT, which has been decided by a group of clinicians to be the most common way of expressing the meaning of the concept.
[src:snomed-terminology/snomed-ct] Synonyms are additional terms and phrases used to refer to this concept.
[src:snomed-terminology/snomed-ct] They do not have to be unique or unambiguous.
[src:snomed-terminology/snomed-ct] SNOMED CT assigns each concept a semantic tag.
[src:snomed-terminology/snomed-ct] It is present in parentheses in Fully Specified Name of each concept.
[src:snomed-terminology/snomed-ct] There can be multiple semantic tags used within each SNOMED CT top level hierarchy.
[src:snomed-terminology/snomed-ct] For example, top level hierarchy of Pharmaceutical/biologic Product uses semantic tags of: product, medicinal product, medicinal product form and clinical drug.
[src:snomed-terminology/snomed-ct] Only one semantic tag can be used for each concept.
[src:snomed-terminology/snomed-ct] SNOMED CT can be characterized as a multilingual thesaurus with an ontological foundation.
[src:snomed-terminology/snomed-ct] Thesaurus-like features are concept–term relations such as the synonymous descriptions "Acute coryza", "Acute nasal catarrh", "Acute rhinitis", "Common cold" (as well as Spanish "resfrío común" and "rinitis infecciosa") for the concept 82272006.
[src:snomed-terminology/snomed-ct] Under ontological scrutiny, SNOMED-CT is a class hierarchy (with extensive overlap of classes in contrast to typical statistical classifications like ICD).
[src:snomed-terminology/snomed-ct] This means that the SNOMED CT concept 82272006 defines the class of all the individual disease instances that match the criteria for "common cold" (e.g., one patient may have "head cold" noted in their record, and another may have "Acute coryza"; both can be found as instances of "common cold").
[src:snomed-terminology/snomed-ct] The superclass (Is-A) Relation relates classes in terms of inclusion of their members.
[src:snomed-terminology/snomed-ct] That is, all individual "cold-processes" are also included in all superclasses of the class Common Cold, such as Viral upper respiratory tract infection (Figure).
[src:snomed-terminology/snomed-ct] SNOMED CT's relational statements are basically triplets of the form Concept1 – Relationx – Concept2, with Relationx being from a small number of relation types (called linkage concepts), e.g.
[src:snomed-terminology/snomed-ct] The interpretation of these triplets is (implicitly) based on the semantics of a simple Description logic (DL).
[src:snomed-terminology/snomed-ct] In the *Common cold* example, the concept description is "primitive", which means that necessary criteria are given that must be met for each instance, without being sufficient for classifying a disorder as an instance of *Common Cold* .
[src:snomed-terminology/snomed-ct] This means that every individual disorder for which all definitional criteria are met can be classified as an instance of Viral upper respiratory tract infection.
[src:snomed-terminology/snomed-ct] For understanding the modelling, it is also important to look at the stated view of a concept versus the inferred view of the concept.
[src:snomed-terminology/snomed-ct] In further considering the state view, SNOMED CT used in the past a modelling approach referred to as 'proximal parent' approach.
[src:snomed-terminology/snomed-ct] After 2015, a superior approach called "proximal primitive parent" has been adopted.
[src:snomed-terminology/snomed-ct] SNOMED CT provides a compositional syntax that can be used to create expressions that represent clinical ideas which are not explicitly represented by SNOMED CT concepts.
[src:snomed-terminology/snomed-ct] This mechanism exists because it is challenging to create and maintain all possible concepts upfront (as precoordinated concepts).
[src:snomed-terminology/snomed-ct] For example, there is no explicit concept for a "third degree burn of left index finger caused by hot water".
[src:snomed-terminology/snomed-ct] Such expressions are said to have been 'postcoordinated'.
[src:snomed-terminology/snomed-ct] Post-coordination avoids the need to create large numbers of defined Concepts within SNOMED CT.
[src:snomed-terminology/snomed-ct] However, many systems only allow for precoordinated representations.
[src:snomed-terminology/snomed-ct] Reliable analysis and comparison of post-coordinated expressions is possible using appropriate algorithms machinery to efficiently process the expression taking account of the underlying description logic.
[src:snomed-terminology/snomed-ct] Major Electronic Health Record Systems (EHRS) have repeatedly complained to IHTSDO and other standards organizations about the "complexity" of post-coordinated expressions.
[src:snomed-terminology/snomed-ct] For example, the postcoordinated expression above can be transformed using a set of standard rules to the following "normal form expression" which enables comparison with similar concepts.
[src:snomed-terminology/snomed-ct] Postcoordination is an important desirable feature of a terminology.
[src:snomed-terminology/snomed-ct] Prior 2020, International Classification of Diseases (ICD) did not allow post-coordination and SNOMED CT was the only terminology that supported postcoordination.
[src:snomed-terminology/snomed-ct] Since 2020, a new version of ICD-11 now also supports postcoordination.
[src:snomed-terminology/snomed-ct] The International Edition of SNOMED CT only includes human terms.
[src:snomed-terminology/snomed-ct] In 2014, clearly veterinary concepts were moved into a SNOMED CT veterinary extension.
[src:snomed-terminology/snomed-ct] This extension is managed by the Veterinary Terminology Services Lab at the Va-Md College of Veterinary Medicine at Virginia Tech.
[src:snomed-terminology/snomed-ct] Earlier SNOMED versions had faceted structure ordered by semantic axes, requiring that more complex situations required to be coded by a coordination of different codes.
[src:snomed-terminology/snomed-ct] On the one hand, the necessity of post-coordination was perceived as a user-unfriendly obstacle, which has certainly contributed to the low adoption of early SNOMED versions.
[src:snomed-terminology/snomed-ct] On the other hand, uniform coding was difficult to obtain.
[src:snomed-terminology/snomed-ct] E.g., *Acute appendicitis* could be post-coordinated in three different ways with no means to compute semantic equivalences.
[src:snomed-terminology/snomed-ct] SNOMED RT had addressed this problem by introducing description logic formula.
[src:snomed-terminology/snomed-ct] With the addition of CTV3 many concepts were redefined using formal expressions.
[src:snomed-terminology/snomed-ct] However, the fusion with CTV3, as a historically grown terminology with many close-to user descriptions, introduced some problems which still affect SNOMED CT.
[src:snomed-terminology/snomed-ct] In addition to a confusing taxonomic web of many hierarchical levels with massive multiple inheritance (e.g. there are 36 taxonomic ancestors for *Acute appendicitis*), many ambiguous, context-dependent concepts have found their way into SNOMED CT.
[src:snomed-terminology/snomed-ct] Pre-coordination was sometimes pushed to extremes, so there are, for example, 350 different concepts for burns found on the head.
[src:snomed-terminology/snomed-ct] A further phenomenon which characterizes parts of SNOMED CT is the so-called *epistemic intrusion*.
[src:snomed-terminology/snomed-ct] In principle, the task of terminology (and even an ontology) should be limited to providing context-free term or class meanings.
[src:snomed-terminology/snomed-ct] The contextualization of these representational units should be ideally the task of an information model.
[src:snomed-terminology/snomed-ct] Human language is misleading here, as we use syntactically similar expression to represent categorically distinct entities, e.g.
[src:snomed-terminology/snomed-ct] The first one refers to a real pregnancy, the second one to a piece of (uncertain) *information*.
[src:snomed-terminology/snomed-ct] In SNOMED CT most (but not all) of these context-dependent concepts are concentrated in the subhierachy *Situation with explicit context*.
[src:snomed-terminology/snomed-ct] A major reason for why such concepts cannot be dispensed with is that SNOMED CT takes on, in many cases, the functionality of information models, as the latter do not exist in a given implementation.
[src:snomed-terminology/snomed-ct] With the establishment of IHTSDO, SNOMED CT became more accessible to a wider audience.
[src:snomed-terminology/snomed-ct] Criticism of the state of the terminology was sparked by numerous substantive weaknesses as well as on the lack of quality assurance measures.
[src:snomed-terminology/snomed-ct] From the beginning IHTSDO was open regarding such (also academic) criticism.
[src:snomed-terminology/snomed-ct] In the last few years considerable progress has been made regarding quality assurance and tooling.
[src:snomed-terminology/snomed-ct] The need for a more principled ontological foundation was gradually accepted, as well as a better understanding of description logic semantics.
[src:snomed-terminology/snomed-ct] Redesign priorities were formulated regarding observables, disorders, findings, substances, organisms etc.
[src:snomed-terminology/snomed-ct] Translation guidelines were elaborated as well as guidelines for content submission requests and a strategy for the inclusion of pre-coordinated content.
[src:snomed-terminology/snomed-ct] There are still known deficiencies regarding the "ontological commitment" of SNOMED CT, e.g., the clarification of which kind of entity is an instance of a given SNOMED CT concept.
[src:snomed-terminology/snomed-ct] The same term can be interpreted as a disorder or a patient with a disorder, for example *Tumour* might denote a process or a piece of tissue; *Allergy* may denote an allergic reaction or just an allergic disposition.
[src:snomed-terminology/snomed-ct] A more recent strategy is the use of rigorously typed upper-level ontologies to disambiguate SNOMED CT content.
[src:snomed-terminology/snomed-ct] The increased take-up of SNOMED CT for research into applications in daily use across the world to support patient care is leading to a larger engaged community.
[src:snomed-terminology/snomed-ct] This has led to an increase in the resource allocated to authoring SNOMED CT terms as well as to an increase in collaboration to take SNOMED CT into a robust industry used standard.
[src:snomed-terminology/snomed-ct] This is leading to an increase in the number of software tools and development of materials that contribute to knowledge base to support implementation.
[src:snomed-terminology/snomed-ct] Several on-line communities that focus on particular aspects of SNOMED CT and its implementation are also developing.
[src:snomed-terminology/snomed-ct] In theory, description logic reasoning can be applied to any new candidate post-coordinated expressions in order to assess whether it is a parent or ancestor of, a child or other descendant of, or semantically equivalent to any existing concept from the existing pre-coordinated concepts.
[src:snomed-terminology/snomed-ct] However, partly as the continuing fall-out from the merger with CTV3, SNOMED still contains undiscovered semantically duplicate primitive and defined concepts.
[src:snomed-terminology/snomed-ct] Additionally, many concepts remain primitive whilst their semantics can also be legitimately defined in terms of other primitives and roles concurrently in the system.
[src:snomed-terminology/snomed-ct] Because of these omissions and actual or possible redundancies of semantic content, real-world performance of algorithms to infer subsumption or semantic equivalence will be unpredictably imperfect.
[src:snomed-terminology/snomed-ct] Using consistent rules is important for the quality of SNOMED CT.
[src:snomed-terminology/snomed-ct] To that end, in 2009, a prototype Machine Readable Concept Model (MRCM) was created by the SNOMED CT team.
[src:snomed-terminology/snomed-ct] In a follow-up work, this model is being revised to utilize SNOMED CT expression constraints.
[src:snomed-terminology/snomed-ct] SNOMED CT is a clinical terminology designed to capture and represent patient data for clinical purposes.
[src:snomed-terminology/snomed-ct] Both systems use standardized definitions and form a common medical language used within electronic health record (EHR) systems.
[src:snomed-terminology/snomed-ct] SNOMED CT enables information input into an EHR system during the course of patient care, while ICD facilitates information retrieval, or output, for secondary data purposes.
[src:snomed-terminology/snomed-ct] In 2010s, the advantage of SNOMED CT over ICD was the multiple parent hierarchy of SNOMED CT.
[src:snomed-terminology/snomed-ct] Since 2020 release of ICD 11, this advantage is less important because ICD-11 foundational level allows an ICD 11 concept to have multiple parents.
[src:snomed-terminology/snomed-ct] LOINC is a terminology that contains laboratory tests.
[src:snomed-terminology/snomed-ct] Since 2017, SNOMED International started creating terms for LOINC components and created a set of SNOMED CT expressions that capture the meaning of many LOINC terms.
[src:snomed-terminology/snomed-ct] There is overlap between MedDRA and SNOMED CT that is not beneficial for pharmaceutical industry.
[src:snomed-terminology/snomed-ct] In 2021, two maps map between SNOMED CT and MedDRA were jointly published by both organizations (from SNOMED CT to MedDRA and from MedDRA to SNOMED CT).
[src:snomed-terminology/snomed-ct] The use of SNOMED CT in production systems requires a license.
[src:snomed-terminology/snomed-ct] Affiliate license (dependent on the number of end users).
[src:snomed-terminology/snomed-ct] LDCs (least developed countries) can use SNOMED CT without charges.
[src:snomed-terminology/snomed-ct] For scientific research in medical informatics, for demonstrations or evaluation purposes SNOMED CT sources can be freely downloaded and used.
[src:snomed-terminology/snomed-ct] The original SNOMED CT sources in tabular form are accessible by registered users of the Unified Medical Language System (UMLS) who have signed an agreement.
[src:snomed-terminology/snomed-ct] Numerous online and offline browsers are available.
[src:snomed-terminology/snomed-ct] Those wishing to obtain a license for its use and to download SNOMED CT should contact their National Release Centre, links to which are provided on the IHTSDO website.
[src:snomed-terminology/snomed-ct] To facilitate adoption of SNOMED CT and use of SNOMED CT in other standards, there are license free subsets.
[src:snomed-terminology/snomed-ct] For example, a set of 7 314 codes and descriptions is free for use by users of DICOM-compliant software (without restriction to IHTSDO member countries).
[src:snomed-terminology/snomed-ct] GPS was released in Sep 2019 and contains 21 782 concepts.
[src:snomed-terminology/snomed-ct] SNOMED CT concepts typically belong to a single hierarchy (with the exception of drug-device combined concepts).
[src:snomed-terminology/snomed-ct] Some hierarchies, have a concept model defined (e.g., clinical findings).
[src:snomed-terminology/snomed-ct] For other domains (e.g., Organism, Substance, Qualifier value), there is no concept model yet defined.
[src:snomed-terminology/snomed-ct] Concept in this hierarchy represent procedures performed on a patient.
[src:snomed-terminology/snomed-ct] There is a well-established defined concept model for procedures.
[src:snomed-terminology/snomed-ct] Procedure site (direct or indirect) specifies on what part of body the procedure is performed.
[src:snomed-terminology/snomed-ct] A separate set of rules exist for evaluation procedures.
[src:snomed-terminology/snomed-ct] Evaluation procedures are procedures where evidence is evaluated to support the determination of a value, inference or conclusion.
[src:snomed-terminology/snomed-ct] Evaluation procedures have additional attributes, such as 'Has specimen','Property' or 'Measurement method'.
[src:snomed-terminology/snomed-ct] As of 2016, the Event hierarchy does not have a concept model defined.
[src:snomed-terminology/snomed-ct] In 2006, some concepts from the 'Clinical Finding' hierarchy were moved to the Event hierarchy.
[src:snomed-terminology/snomed-ct] Those concepts retained some of their attributes.
[src:snomed-terminology/snomed-ct] SNOMED International is working on creating a concept model for observable entities.
[src:snomed-terminology/snomed-ct] Body parts represent one of the largest hierarchies within SNOMED CT.
[src:snomed-terminology/snomed-ct] The modeling is based on Foundational Model of Anatomy but it differs from the model in some aspects (e.g., region is taken as 3D region and not a 2D region).
[src:snomed-terminology/snomed-ct] Important attributes include: 'Laterality', several types of 'Part of' relationships, and 'Is a'.
[src:snomed-terminology/snomed-ct] Pharmaceutical and biologic products are modeled using constructs of active ingredient, presentation strength, and basis of strength.
[src:snomed-terminology/snomed-ct] Since 2018, harmonization of SNOMED CT drug content with IDMP standard is an editorial goal.
[src:snomed-terminology/snomed-ct] Concept that represents a concrete drug product as used in clinical practice.
[src:snomed-terminology/snomed-ct] Concept representing how the product is delivered.
[src:snomed-terminology/snomed-ct] For example, 385219001 | Conventional release solution for injection (dose form) |.
[src:snomed-terminology/snomed-ct] Several mechanisms are employed to ensure this.
[src:snomed-terminology/snomed-ct] Machine readable concept model is used to check for compliance with a set of rules.
[src:snomed-terminology/snomed-ct] Rules for creating fully specified name for a concept define allowed and not allowed patterns.
[src:snomed-terminology/snomed-ct] When defining a concept, a proximal primitive parent rule is used (in stated definition) to employ best description logic derived classification of concepts.
[src:snomed-terminology/snomed-ct] Separate conventions govern grouping of relationships.
[src:snomed-terminology/snomed-ct] Ability to group related relationships is an important strength of SNOMED CT.
[src:snomed-terminology/snomed-ct] Rules in Machine Readable Concept Model (MRCM) specify by domain which relationships are never grouped (e.g., 'Is a' or 'Laterality' attributes) and which relationships are always grouped (e.g., 'Finding site').
[src:snomed-terminology/snomed-ct] For correct subsumption inference, some relationships may be in a group but consist of a single relationship.
[src:snomed-terminology/snomed-ct] Another convention for SNOMED CT international edition is to avoid creating intermediate primitive concepts (unless medically necessary and impossible to define with existing concept model).
[src:snomed-terminology/snomed-ct] An intermediate primitive (=not defined) concept is a non-defined concept that has children concepts and parent concepts.
[src:snomed-terminology/snomed-ct] This convention is related to the use of description logic to facilitate terminology maintenance.
[src:snomed-terminology/snomed-ct] Because primitive concepts can not be processed by the description logic classifier, the maintenance of such concepts relies solely on human editors.
[src:snomed-terminology/snomed-ct] Adding new intermediate primitive concepts requires changes to all affected concepts and is demanding in terms of terminology maintenance.
[src:snomed-terminology/systematized-nomenclature-of-medicine] The **Systematized Nomenclature of Medicine** (**SNOMED**) is a systematic, computer-processable collection of medical terms, in human and veterinary medicine, to provide codes, terms, synonyms and definitions which cover anatomy, diseases, findings, procedures, microorganisms, substances, etc.
[src:snomed-terminology/systematized-nomenclature-of-medicine] It allows a consistent way to index, store, retrieve, and aggregate medical data across specialties and sites of care.
[src:snomed-terminology/systematized-nomenclature-of-medicine] Although now international, SNOMED was started in the U.S. by the College of American Pathologists (CAP) in 1973 and revised into the 1990s.
[src:snomed-terminology/systematized-nomenclature-of-medicine] In 2002 CAP's SNOMED Reference Terminology (SNOMED RT) was merged with, and expanded by, the National Health Service's Clinical Terms Version 3 (previously known as the Read codes) to produce SNOMED CT.
[src:snomed-terminology/systematized-nomenclature-of-medicine] Versions of SNOMED released prior to 2001 were based on a multiaxial, hierarchical classification system.
[src:snomed-terminology/systematized-nomenclature-of-medicine] As in any such system, a disease may be located in a body organ (anatomy), which results in a code in a topography axis and may lead to morphological alterations represented by a morphology code.
[src:snomed-terminology/systematized-nomenclature-of-medicine] In 2002 the first release of SNOMED CT adopted a completely different structure.
[src:snomed-terminology/systematized-nomenclature-of-medicine] A sub-type hierarchy, supported by defining relationships based on description logic, replaced the axes described in this article.
[src:snomed-terminology/systematized-nomenclature-of-medicine] Versions of SNOMED prior to SNOMED CT are planned to be formally deprecated from 2017.
[src:snomed-terminology/systematized-nomenclature-of-medicine] Therefore, readers interested in current information about SNOMED are directed to the article on SNOMED CT.
[src:snomed-terminology/systematized-nomenclature-of-medicine] SNOMED was designed as a comprehensive nomenclature of clinical medicine for the purpose of accurately storing and/or retrieving records of clinical care in human and veterinary medicine.
[src:snomed-terminology/systematized-nomenclature-of-medicine] Côté, the first editorial chair, was that SNOMED would become the periodic table of elements of medicine because of its definitional organization beyond the hierarchical design.
[src:snomed-terminology/systematized-nomenclature-of-medicine] SNOMED was originally conceived by Côté as an extension of the design of the Systematized Nomenclature of Pathology (SNOP) applicable for all medicine.
[src:snomed-terminology/systematized-nomenclature-of-medicine] SNOP was originally designed by Arnold Pratt to describe pathological specimens according to their morphology and anatomy (topography).
[src:snomed-terminology/systematized-nomenclature-of-medicine] The ambitious development of SNOMED required many more axes (see multi-axial design, below).
[src:snomed-terminology/systematized-nomenclature-of-medicine] SNOMED was jointly proposed for development to the College of American Pathologists by Côté and Pratt.
[src:snomed-terminology/systematized-nomenclature-of-medicine] The former was appointed as editorial chair of the Committee on Nomenclature and Classification of Diseases of the CAP and developed the SNOMED from 1973 to 1997.
[src:snomed-terminology/systematized-nomenclature-of-medicine] In 1998, Kent Spackman was appointed to chair this committee and spearheaded the transformation of the multi-axis systems into a highly computable form (See SNOMED CT): a directed acyclic graph anchored in formal representation logic.
[src:snomed-terminology/systematized-nomenclature-of-medicine] In 2007, the newly formed International Health Terminology Standards Development Organisation (IHTSDO) acquired all the Intellectual Property of SNOMED CT and all antecedent SNOMED versions.
[src:snomed-terminology/systematized-nomenclature-of-medicine] SNOMED was designed from its inception with complex concepts defined in terms of simpler ones.
[src:snomed-terminology/systematized-nomenclature-of-medicine] For example, a disease can be defined in terms of its abnormal anatomy, abnormal functions and morphology.
[src:snomed-terminology/systematized-nomenclature-of-medicine] In some cases, the etiology of the disease is known and can be attributed to an infectious agent, a physical trauma or a chemical or pharmaceutical agent.
[src:snomed-terminology/systematized-nomenclature-of-medicine] The current concept uses eleven (11) axes that comprise terms organised in hierarchical trees.
[src:snomed-terminology/terminology] Terminology is a discipline that systematically studies the "labelling or designating of concepts" particular to one or more subject fields or domains of human activity.
[src:snomed-terminology/terminology] It does this through the research and analysis of terms in context for the purpose of documenting and promoting consistent usage.
[src:snomed-terminology/terminology] Terminology can be limited to one or more languages (for example, "multilingual terminology" and "bilingual terminology"), or may have an interdisciplinarity focus on the use of terms in different fields.
[src:snomed-terminology/terminology] Ad hoc terminology is prevalent in the translation profession, where a translation for a specific term (or group of terms) is required quickly to solve a particular translation problem.
[src:snomed-terminology/terminology] Nomenclature comprises types of terminology especially having to do with general ontology, applied ontology, and taxonomy (categorizations and classifications, such as taxonomy for life forms, taxonomy for search engines, and so on).
[src:snomed-terminology/terminology] A **terminologist** intends to hone categorical organization by improving the accuracy and content of its terminology.
[src:snomed-terminology/terminology] Technical industries and standardization institutes compile their own glossaries.
[src:snomed-terminology/terminology] This provides the consistency needed in the various areas—fields and branches, movements and specialties—to work with core terminology to then offer material for the discipline's traditional and doctrinal literature.
[src:snomed-terminology/terminology] Terminology is also then key in boundary-crossing problems, such as in language translation and social epistemology.
[src:snomed-terminology/terminology] Terminology helps to build bridges and to extend one area into another.
[src:snomed-terminology/terminology] Translators research the terminology of the languages they translate.
[src:snomed-terminology/terminology] Terminology is taught alongside translation in universities and translation schools.
[src:snomed-terminology/terminology] Large translation departments and translation bureaus have a *Terminology* section.
[src:snomed-terminology/terminology] The main objects of terminological studies are special lexical units (or special lexemes), first of all terms.
[src:snomed-terminology/terminology] They are analysed from the point of view of their origin, formal structure, their meanings and also functional features.
[src:snomed-terminology/terminology] Terminological research started seventy years ago and was especially fruitful at the last forty years.
[src:snomed-terminology/terminology] At that time the main types of special lexical units, such as terms proper, nomens, terminoids, prototerms, preterms and quasiterms were singled out and studied.
[src:snomed-terminology/terminology] The main principles of terminological work were elaborated, terminologies of the leading European languages belonging to many subject fields were described and analysed.
[src:snomed-terminology/terminology] Terminological theories include general theory of terminology, socioterminology, communicative theory of terminology, sociocognitive terminology, frame-based terminology, and cultural terminology.
